  "opinion": "As a plumber with a background in hands-on work and a family that values practical skills, I've seen firsthand how stereotype threat can quietly undermine potential in STEM fields. Stereotype threat occurs when people feel at risk of confirming negative stereotypes about their social group, which can lead to anxiety that impairs performance. For example, when a girl in my daughter’s school class is told she’s 'not good at math,' it’s not just a simple comment—it’s a potential trigger that can make her doubt her abilities. In STEM, where many feel pressure to conform to gender norms, this threat can be especially damaging. I’ve worked with students who’ve avoided engineering because they thought they weren’t 'logical enough,' even though they excelled in other areas. The good news is that addressing stereotype threat isn’t about changing the stereotypes themselves but about creating supportive environments where everyone feels safe to try. At my part-time job, I’ve seen how simple things like encouraging kids to explore science through hands-on projects—like building small water systems—can build confidence. It’s important to normalize diverse voices in STEM without making it feel like an obligation. As a Christian, I believe in treating everyone with dignity and respect, so I think we should focus on mentorship and inclusive practices that help people see themselves as capable. Ultimately, the key is to shift from 'you can’t do this' to 'you belong here.'",
